 aHow is ethnicity viewed by scholars of different academic disciplines? Can its emergences be compared in various regions of the world? How can it be conceptualized with specific reference to distinct historical periods?This book shows in a uniquely and innovative way the broad range of approaches to the political uses of ethnicity, both in contemporary settings and from a historical perspective. Its scope is multidisciplinary and spans across the globe.It is a suitable resource for teaching material. With its short contributions, it conveys central points of how to understand and analyze ethnicity as a political resource.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched - KU Select 2016: Frontlist Collection  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCultural pluralismvCongresses. 0aEthnicityxHistoryy20th centuryvCongresses. 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspectsvCongresses. 0aInterdisciplinary researchvCongresses. 0aMinoritiesvCongresses. 0aMulticulturalismvCongresses. 4aAfrica. 4aAsia. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCultural Theory. 4aCulture. 4aEthnology. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aLatin America. 4aPolicy. 4aPolitical Theory. 4aPolitics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAsia.  aCultural Studies.  aCultural Theory.  aCulture.  aEthnology.  aEurope.  aHistory.  aLatin America.  aPolicy.  aPolitical Theory.  aPolitics.1 aAlbiez-Wieck, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntweiler, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Anja Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re